The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Dec. 24: The government issued bonds worth Rs 4,000 crore to 16 fertiliser companies to compensate them for selling the key agricultural input to farmers at low prices. The 14-year special bonds carry a coupon rate of 6.20 per cent. Indian Farmers Fertiliser Co-operative Ltd has received the largest issued share.                             
	 Mumbai, Dec. 24: The Securities and Exchange Board of India has imposed a penalty of Rs 10 lakh on Kotak Securities. Sebi said this penalty had been levied as the brokerage violated its regulations while offering margin trading facility to its investors.                            
	 Washington, Dec. 24: Consumers in the US cut their spending in November and orders for costly manufactured goods slumped again, while claims for jobless aid hit a 26-year high last week as recession tightened its grip on the country.                             
	 Mumbai, Dec. 24: India will invest in uranium mines in Russia, Kazakhstan and a few other countries to acquire 50 per cent ownership to ensure uninterrupted supply of fuel for its nuclear power plants, S.K. Jain, chairman and managing director of Nuclear Power Corporation of India, said.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 24: The Supreme Court has held that banks are not liable to pay interest tax on subsidies they get from the RBI for giving concessional loans to exporters. The RBI gives export subsidy to banks to make good their losses because of extending export credit at a lower rate of interest.                            
	 Mumbai, Dec. 24: The Life Insurance Corporation of India has increased its stake in HDFC Bank to over 5 per cent by acquiring shares in the open market. The LIC purchased 1.6 lakh shares, taking its stake in the company to 5.01 per cent.                            
	 Mumbai, Dec. 24: Justice K.K. Tated, one of the two judges hearing the Reliance gas dispute case, has been transferred to the Aurangabad bench of Bombay High Court.                                                                                                                         
